   <titles>
      <title>Invertible Linear Transformations</title>
      <plain.title>Invertible Linear Maps</plain.title>
   </titles>
   <intro>
      <block>
         <block.body>
            <para>
               <para.body>Recall: a linear function <math>
                     <latex>L\from \RNr[n] \to \RNr[n]</latex>
                  </math> is invertible if its transformation effect can be reversed. Now let <math>
                     <latex>V</latex>
                  </math> and <math>
                     <latex>W</latex>
                  </math> are subvector spaces of <math>
                     <latex>\RNr[k]</latex>
                  </math>. Nicely enough, a linear function <math>
                     <latex>L\from V\to W</latex>
                  </math> is invertible exactly when there exists a linear map <math>
                     <latex>M\from W\to V</latex>
                  </math> such that <math>
                     <latex>L</latex>
                  </math> and <math>
                     <latex>M</latex>
                  </math> reverse each other's transformation effect.</para.body>
            </para>
            <para>
               <para.body>Next we look for criteria to identify invertible linear maps. In this section we show: <math>
                     <latex>L</latex>
                  </math> is invertible if and only if the matrix representing <math>
                     <latex>L</latex>
                  </math> with respect to any choice of ordered bases of <math>
                     <latex>V</latex>
                  </math> and <math>
                     <latex>W</latex>
                  </math> is invertible. We will develop additional criteria in subsequent sections.</para.body>
            </para>
         </block.body>
      </block>
   </intro>
   <body>
      <block>
         <block.body>
            <def type="Definition" id="Def_InvertibleLinearMapGeneral">
               <caption>Invertible linear transformation</caption>
               <associate type="Explanation">
                  <info>
                     <info.caption>Explanation</info.caption>
                     <para>
                        <para.body>The relationship between <math>
                              <latex>L</latex>
                           </math> and its inverse <math>
                              <latex>M</latex>
                           </math> is the following:</para.body>
                     </para>
                     <ol>
                        <li>
                           <para>
                              <para.body>The identity <math>
                                    <latex>M\Comp L = \Id[V]</latex>
                                 </math> asserts that <math>
                                    <latex>M</latex>
                                 </math> reverses the transformation effect of <math>
                                    <latex>L</latex>
                                 </math>.</para.body>
                           </para>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                           <para>
                              <para.body>The identity <math>
                                    <latex>L\Comp M = \Id[W]</latex>
                                 </math> asserts that <math>
                                    <latex>L</latex>
                                 </math> reverses the transformation effect of <math>
                                    <latex>M</latex>
                                 </math>.</para.body>
                           </para>
                        </li>
                     </ol>
                  </info>
               </associate>
               <def.body>
                  <para>
                     <para.body>A linear map <math>
                           <latex>L\from V\to W</latex>
                        </math> of subvector spaces of <math>
                           <latex>\RNr[k]</latex>
                        </math> is called invertible if there exists a linear map <math>
                           <latex>M\from W\to V</latex>
                        </math> such that
				</para.body>
                     <index.glossary>
                        <term>invertible</term>
                        <term>linear transformation</term>
                        <info>
                           <info.caption>Invertible linear transformation</info.caption>
                           <para>
                              <para.body>Definition of the concept: A linear map <math>
                                    <latex>L\from V\to W</latex>
                                 </math> of subvector spaces of <math>
                                    <latex>\RNr[k]</latex>
                                 </math> is invertible, if there exists a linear map <math>
                                    <latex>M\from W\to V</latex>
                                 </math> such that</para.body>
                           </para>
                           <math.display>
                              <latex>M\Comp L = \Id[V] \quad\text{and}\quad L\Comp M = \Id[W]</latex>
                           </math.display>
                        </info>
                     </index.glossary>
                  </para>
                  <math.display>
                     <latex>M\Comp L = \Id[V] \quad\text{and}\quad L\Comp M = \Id[W]</latex>
                  </math.display>
                  <para>
                     <para.body>In this case we call <math>
                           <latex>M</latex>
                        </math> the inverse of <math>
                           <latex>L</latex>
                        </math> and write <math>
                           <latex>M=L^{-1}</latex>
                        </math>.</para.body>
                  </para>
               </def.body>
            </def>
            <para>
               <para.body>Now to the question: How do we test whether a given linear transformation <math>
                     <latex>L\from V\to W</latex>
                  </math> is invertible?</para.body>
            </para>
